V-meoqyHTIDeV8obk7d1E2o8qo1qc1XegBp6n\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Fixing test failures**\\n\\nI need to address some test failures related to the Groovy InvokerHelper. The user provided details about the issue, suggesting no runs of tests are necessary. It seems that there's a problem with invoking static methods on a Class object, which may relate to how closures are handled. I'm considering removing the Groovy runtime test, but I'm not sure how to improve coverage, as it appears dynamic access isn't being captured correctly. I need to think more about this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing test coverage issues**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether the source report from nativeTestCompile might help before running tests. It seems dynamic-access coverage should be tracking stack frames in the native-image compile, but the existing reports show a lack of coverage. After running tests, it looks like the report doesn't update correctly, maybe because it reads from the compile report instead. I wonder if invoking class$ through MethodHandle is causing the uncovered status. There are many things to consider about reflection and instrumentation in tests!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Focusing on active class testing**\\n\\nI need to concentrate on the active class. The generated closure's doCall directly references \\\"instanceof Argument,\\\" without using Class.forName. The class$ method isn't in doCall because the compiler optimized it to a class literal. While the reported call site exists, it seems inactive except for direct invocations. I wonder if Method.invoke is properly instrumented. The Native Image agent might not be collecting data since tests run on Jacoco-instrumented classes. I need to check the build for effectiveness!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_h7FkejWB2toqJTVnioTNf3W4|fc_0b39208f5b33e8d1016a00a2f45fb4819e8fc1ecf4ed02e4de", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/re